<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1883-01-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1883-01-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="316" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d316">
                    <head>No. 315.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Davis</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Schuyler</persName>.</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-01-22"><hi rend="italic">January</hi> 22,
                            1883</date>.</dateline>
                        <seg rendition="#left">No. 17.]</seg></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to a previous instruction, No. 15,
                        of the 5th instant. I herewith inclose a copy of a dispatch (No. 158, of the
                        25th ultimo),<note n="†" xml:id="d316fn1">See Mr. Wallace to Mr.
                            Frelinghuysen, No. 158, December 25, 1882, <hi rend="italic">post.</hi></note> from Mr. Wallace, our minister at Constantinople, in
                        which he details <pb facs="0606" n="536" xml:id="pg_536"/> the manner in
                        which he was enabled to gain the release of eleven Greeks who were
                        imprisoned for political offenses at Constantinople. Mr. Wallace also
                        incloses a letter from Athens thanking him for his successful efforts in
                        behalf of the prisoners.</p>
                    <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer><signed>JOHN DAVIS,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting
                            Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>